The Gauls however came before that, so that the Romans had scarcely time to meet them eleven miles off, near the spot where the Alia flows into the Tiber. At their first onset the Romans fied like deer, and, neglecting in their panic the defence of the city, found a nearer refuge, most oi them, at Veii. Only those who had formed the right wing made for Rome, where they threw themselves into the Capitol. The Gauls next day marched into the undefended city through the open Colline Gate.
